WEBVTT

00:03.290 --> 00:04.580
♪ Every kiss is a door ♪

00:04.580 --> 00:05.670
♪ Can I knock on yours? ♪

00:05.670 --> 00:08.330
Hey,
did you get any sleep?

00:08.330 --> 00:09.710
I was up all night

00:09.710 --> 00:12.710
trying to figure out
why Cerone hated Ellis.

00:12.710 --> 00:14.540
They were friends,
respected colleagues.

00:14.540 --> 00:15.880
Listen to this --

00:15.880 --> 00:18.790
"Marie's hepatico-J technique
is fascinating...

00:18.790 --> 00:22.290
We were up again all night
talking and drinking."

00:22.290 --> 00:26.080
Meredith:
On average, a healthy heart
beats 115,000 times per day.

00:26.080 --> 00:28.120
And she knew
about Richard.

00:28.120 --> 00:31.420
"MC says
I'm better off without RW.

00:31.420 --> 00:33.250
He was just
a distraction from work."

00:33.250 --> 00:35.250
Maybe she hated Richard.

00:35.250 --> 00:37.460
Maybe she was in love with
Ellis.

00:37.460 --> 00:38.960
Maybe there's a whole
other love triangle

00:38.960 --> 00:40.750
that I don't know about.

00:40.750 --> 00:42.880
When excited,
the heart rate can double.

00:42.880 --> 00:44.500
Are you listening to me?

00:44.500 --> 00:46.380
Um...uh, y-- ah, no.

00:46.380 --> 00:48.000
I'm just -- I'm a little
distracted today.

00:48.000 --> 00:49.330
I'll say.

00:49.330 --> 00:50.500
You just buttered
the kitchen towel,

00:50.500 --> 00:52.670
and your shirt
is on inside out.

00:52.670 --> 00:55.040
What? Mm.

00:55.040 --> 00:56.380
Is this about Clive?

00:56.380 --> 00:57.790
Because I told you
that wasn't your fault.

00:57.790 --> 01:00.040
Yeah...Clive.

01:00.040 --> 01:02.670
Stupid, awful,
married Clive.

01:02.670 --> 01:05.080
Morning, sestras!

01:05.080 --> 01:07.080
Where did you sleep?

01:07.080 --> 01:09.670
Didn't yet.
Going to now.

01:09.670 --> 01:12.080
The heart pumps
2,000 gallons of blood

01:12.080 --> 01:14.620
through your entire body
24 hours a day.

01:14.620 --> 01:16.460
It never rests.

01:16.460 --> 01:19.080
Koracick: [ Singsong voice ]
Morning.

01:21.670 --> 01:23.420
Ugh.

01:23.420 --> 01:25.170
Shall I whip us up
some mean frittatas

01:25.170 --> 01:27.420
or do the slut-rush home?

01:27.420 --> 01:29.790
Second option, please?

01:29.790 --> 01:31.290
Pretty sure
you're hungry.

01:31.290 --> 01:33.120
[ Sighs ]

01:33.120 --> 01:35.290
Can you
take my robe off?

01:35.290 --> 01:37.960
Oh, dessert before breakfast --
I like it.

01:37.960 --> 01:40.790
No, I mean,
take off my robe,

01:40.790 --> 01:44.040
put some clothes on,
and leave my home.

01:44.040 --> 01:45.670
I have to vomit,

01:45.670 --> 01:48.620
and I prefer to do it
in private.

01:48.620 --> 01:50.540
♪ Never let it go, baby ♪

01:50.540 --> 01:52.170
♪ Let it give you life ♪

01:52.170 --> 01:54.540
The heart is the hardest-
working muscle in your body.

01:54.540 --> 01:57.330
But when it's damaged,
it's just like skin.

01:57.330 --> 01:58.420
It scars.

01:58.420 --> 02:00.170
Hey!
God, you had a late night.

02:00.170 --> 02:02.290
Yeah, I wanted to
keep an eye on Kimmie,

02:02.290 --> 02:04.960
but I told Pierce I'd assist
on a case, so...

02:04.960 --> 02:06.460
I'm gonna head back.

02:06.460 --> 02:08.830
Oh, the Dor procedure?
I'm on that, too. Yay!

02:08.830 --> 02:10.750
I feel like I haven't
seen you all week.

02:10.750 --> 02:12.750
And scar tissue can be
very dangerous in a heart.

02:12.750 --> 02:14.290
It weakens it.

02:14.290 --> 02:16.790
What's this?
Oh, fellowship instructions
for next year.

02:16.790 --> 02:18.710
UC San Francisco?

02:18.710 --> 02:20.880
I know. They're ranked
in the top 2% in the country.

02:20.880 --> 02:22.290
Northwestern?

02:22.290 --> 02:24.080
Ambitious,
but I'm applying everywhere.

02:24.080 --> 02:26.380
It's what you do, right?
You coming?

02:26.380 --> 02:31.380
And eventually, a heart
full of scars stops working.

02:31.380 --> 02:34.500
So, basically, I excise
the scarred part of the heart,

02:34.500 --> 02:37.330
and then reshape
the ventricular cavity geometry,

02:37.330 --> 02:39.830
and then sew in a Dacron patch,
which sounds easy,

02:39.830 --> 02:43.170
but this kid's left ventricle
is completely scarred.

02:43.170 --> 02:45.380
A Dor surgery
requires mastery.

02:45.380 --> 02:47.210
You should send the interns
to the gallery to watch.

02:47.210 --> 02:48.540
Oh, forget them.

02:48.540 --> 02:51.120
I'm rearranging my meetings,
so I can watch.

02:51.120 --> 02:53.000
-[ Chuckles ]
-They'll just block my view.

02:53.000 --> 02:54.580
[ Chuckles ] Well,
the interns are away

02:54.580 --> 02:56.670
taking their, uh,
in-training exams.

02:56.670 --> 02:58.620
-Even better.
-Their loss.

02:58.620 --> 03:00.290
Have someone page me when
you're headed to the O.R.

03:12.000 --> 03:13.670
Oh, uh...
[ Chuckles ]

03:13.670 --> 03:14.960
You all right?

03:14.960 --> 03:16.920
Yeah, I'm grood, I'm grood.
I'm good.

03:16.920 --> 03:19.460
[ Laughing ]
I'm not grood.

03:19.460 --> 03:21.710
That's a cross between
great and good.

03:21.710 --> 03:23.380
Hmm.
Yeah.
People say that.

03:23.380 --> 03:24.670
-Okay.
-Mm-hmm.

03:24.670 --> 03:26.920
Um, how you feeling about
that date tonight?

03:26.920 --> 03:28.790
Dinner?

03:28.790 --> 03:30.540
No.

03:30.540 --> 03:31.830
No?

03:31.830 --> 03:34.250
Because I am a surgeon,

03:34.250 --> 03:36.080
and I hold human hearts
in my hands,

03:36.080 --> 03:38.460
and I cannot risk
buttering the wrong ventricle.

03:38.460 --> 03:40.250
You're doing what
to the...ventricle?

03:40.250 --> 03:42.330
I'm saying that
I need to focus today.

03:42.330 --> 03:44.170
I have a major surgery
on a kid and...
[ Sighs ]

03:44.170 --> 03:47.080
...I need to give that
my exclusive focus

03:47.080 --> 03:49.330
and...
you make my hands shake.

03:49.330 --> 03:50.540
-Got it.
-Yes. Sorry.

03:50.540 --> 03:54.790
Mm-hmm.

03:54.790 --> 03:57.460
I can't drink this.
What am I carrying it for?

04:00.040 --> 04:01.290
Are you watching me
walk away?

04:01.290 --> 04:02.250
No. No.

04:04.620 --> 04:06.080
What's his BNP?

04:06.080 --> 04:09.790
Uh, it's 750
and that's after diuresis.

04:09.790 --> 04:12.040
And his ejection fraction
is at 30%,

04:12.040 --> 04:14.290
which is why we have to
do this today.

04:14.290 --> 04:16.170
Do you have any questions
before the surgery?

04:16.170 --> 04:19.040
This surgery shall
slay the dragon forevermore?

04:19.040 --> 04:20.920
He means
the ECMO machine.

04:20.920 --> 04:22.000
They call it "the dragon."

04:22.000 --> 04:23.960
Because
dragons can be slain.

04:23.960 --> 04:26.120
By the right knight
at the right moment,

04:26.120 --> 04:28.040
they can always be slain.

04:28.040 --> 04:30.080
That makes you
his knight in shining armor.

04:30.080 --> 04:32.250
[ Chuckles ]
And you are?

04:32.250 --> 04:34.710
I'm his knight in
shining other-armor.

04:34.710 --> 04:37.960
-[ Chuckles ]
-That's very poetic.

04:37.960 --> 04:39.830
Well,
it is my most fervent hope

04:39.830 --> 04:42.380
that we will slay
this ECMO dragon today.

04:42.380 --> 04:43.710
You don't have to play along
with their "costume play."

04:43.710 --> 04:45.290
It just encourages them.

04:45.290 --> 04:47.880
We're young and in love,
fair mother of mine.

04:47.880 --> 04:51.210
We need all the encouragement
we can get.

04:51.210 --> 04:52.620
[ Softer ]
And it's called cosplay.

04:52.620 --> 04:54.380
In love is great,

04:54.380 --> 04:56.380
but I miss when you only
wore costumes on Halloween.

04:56.380 --> 05:00.420
Why should the world be dull and
lifeless 364 days of the year?

05:00.420 --> 05:03.080
That's why
he's the master of my heart.

05:03.080 --> 05:04.620
[ Sighs ]
First love, right?

05:04.620 --> 05:10.330
♪♪

05:10.330 --> 05:12.750
Are you ticklish, Alex?
[ Giggling ]

05:12.750 --> 05:15.790
Okay, stop, no.
We have to focus, okay?

05:15.790 --> 05:20.120
So, the thin, flexible barrier
around a cell is called the --

05:20.120 --> 05:21.290
Why don't we just
study later?

05:21.290 --> 05:22.920
Because
you have a test.

05:22.920 --> 05:25.830
Yeah, well...
I kind of took it this morning.

05:25.830 --> 05:27.830
W--
Are you serious?

05:27.830 --> 05:31.040
[ Laughing ]
No, you did not.
Yeah.

05:31.040 --> 05:32.120
Then what are we
doing here?

05:32.120 --> 05:34.790
Duh, Alex.

05:34.790 --> 05:36.330
I wanted to see you.

05:42.620 --> 05:45.250
[ Door opens ]

05:45.250 --> 05:47.670
I thought we could
discuss business over doughnuts.

05:47.670 --> 05:49.880
I brought you chocolate-frosted,
your favorite,

05:49.880 --> 05:51.710
but I also brought
almond croissants

05:51.710 --> 05:53.000
in case your tastes
have matured.

05:55.500 --> 05:57.330
Or we can feed it
to the mouse.

06:00.580 --> 06:02.790
Why did you pretend
everything is okay

06:02.790 --> 06:04.920
and not mention that you've had
a falling out with my mother?

06:04.920 --> 06:07.330
I didn't pretend anything.

06:07.330 --> 06:09.380
You waltzed in here
like it's a family reunion,

06:09.380 --> 06:11.710
and now you're plying me
with sugar like I'm a child.

06:11.710 --> 06:15.040
My affection for you has
nothing to do with your mother.

06:15.040 --> 06:18.670
Yes, we had a falling out,
but I thought you knew.

06:18.670 --> 06:20.670
Well, I didn't.

06:20.670 --> 06:23.290
So now I need you to tell me
why you're really here.

06:23.290 --> 06:25.250
Darling,
you reached out to me --

06:25.250 --> 06:27.670
Are you even going to
let me license the patent?

06:27.670 --> 06:31.790
Whatever happened between you
and my mother, it's --

06:31.790 --> 06:34.040
it has nothing to do with me,

06:34.040 --> 06:36.790
so please let's not
let a petty disagreement

06:36.790 --> 06:40.290
get in the way of what could be
a landmark medical breakthrough.

06:40.290 --> 06:43.210
There is nothing petty here,
Meredith.

06:43.210 --> 06:45.080
Are you interested in my story
or only your own?

06:47.380 --> 06:49.040
Hey.

06:49.040 --> 06:51.580
I ran a blood gas,
CBC, and BMP,

06:51.580 --> 06:54.250
and I corrected Charlie's
magnesium and potassium levels.

06:54.250 --> 06:56.880
Are you seriously
mad about this?

06:56.880 --> 06:59.040
About what?

06:59.040 --> 07:01.830
You --
You have been silent,

07:01.830 --> 07:03.960
and you've barely looked at me
since you saw my applications.

07:03.960 --> 07:05.330
You did the same thing
your fifth year.

07:05.330 --> 07:07.210
I know you applied to
half of the same places!

07:07.210 --> 07:09.080
Which is why
I didn't say anything.

07:09.080 --> 07:10.080
Go ahead
and do what you want.

07:11.460 --> 07:13.500
Change of plans.
UNOS called.

07:13.500 --> 07:16.460
There is a donor heart in Oregon
for Charlie Peterson.

07:16.460 --> 07:17.580
So, the Dor procedure's
now a transplant.

07:17.580 --> 07:19.380
Yeah.

07:19.380 --> 07:22.500
You --
Which is a good thing, right?

07:22.500 --> 07:24.250
This was
my Michelangelo moment.

07:24.250 --> 07:26.080
Surgical architecture.

07:26.080 --> 07:28.750
But we're saving
a kid's life!

07:28.750 --> 07:30.500
And we're -- we're giving him
a chance at love,

07:30.500 --> 07:31.960
and I am
a terrible person.

07:31.960 --> 07:33.750
Love?
I was promised mastery.

07:33.750 --> 07:34.880
Now I have to
go do paperwork.

07:34.880 --> 07:36.960
[ Elevator dings ]

07:36.960 --> 07:39.880
I've been on the list for three
years without a single call,

07:39.880 --> 07:42.420
and the day I'm supposed to get
the Dor, they find me a match?

07:42.420 --> 07:44.250
It's poetic, right?

07:44.250 --> 07:46.580
Meant to be.
Just like us.

07:48.500 --> 07:49.540
No.

07:50.880 --> 07:52.170
No what?

07:52.170 --> 07:54.580
No, thank you.

07:54.580 --> 07:57.040
I want the surgery I came here
for on my own heart,

07:57.040 --> 07:58.380
if you please,
brave knight.

07:58.380 --> 08:01.170
The Dor procedure --
while very, very cool --

08:01.170 --> 08:02.790
is not
a permanent solution.

08:02.790 --> 08:04.420
It would just
buy us more time.

08:04.420 --> 08:06.210
The heart transplant is what
we've been waiting for, honey.

08:06.210 --> 08:07.330
That was before.

08:07.330 --> 08:08.750
Before what?

08:08.750 --> 08:10.500
Before Henry.

08:10.500 --> 08:12.830
This scarred heart of mine
fell in love with Henry.

08:12.830 --> 08:14.830
What if the new heart
doesn't love him?

08:14.830 --> 08:16.120
That's not how it works.

08:16.120 --> 08:17.620
Love has nothing to do
with the heart.

08:17.620 --> 08:19.750
Tell that to every poet
in the history of the world.

08:19.750 --> 08:21.880
Adrenaline, dopamine,
and serotonin

08:21.880 --> 08:24.170
are the chemicals in your brain
telling you that you love Henry.

08:24.170 --> 08:25.620
And brain chemicals
eventually fade.

08:25.620 --> 08:27.330
They always do.

08:27.330 --> 08:31.670
I know you think we're foolish
because you're old and jaded.

08:31.670 --> 08:36.380
But this love is exquisite
and I'm not gonna risk it...

08:36.380 --> 08:38.250
even if it only lasts
one more year.

08:38.250 --> 08:41.540
That's, like,
so sweet it hurts.

08:41.540 --> 08:43.830
Brave knight,
I beg of you,

08:43.830 --> 08:46.290
slay the dragon
you came here to slay,

08:46.290 --> 08:49.040
and give the new heart
to someone else.

08:49.040 --> 08:53.290
♪♪

09:05.710 --> 09:06.960
Charlie,
if you decline this heart,

09:06.960 --> 09:08.210
you're just going to
get sicker and sicker

09:08.210 --> 09:09.290
until you can only
look at your boyfriend

09:09.290 --> 09:10.540
through
a hospital window.

09:10.540 --> 09:12.830
Do you think that's romantic?
Do you?

09:12.830 --> 09:13.920
Because it's not.
It's stupid.

09:13.920 --> 09:15.500
Just give me
the papers.

09:15.500 --> 09:16.960
You'll drug him if you have to,
but he's getting that heart.

09:16.960 --> 09:18.790
Mom, no!
Can we just, um --

09:18.790 --> 09:20.960
Can we have a little time?

09:20.960 --> 09:22.750
There is no time. The heart
will go to someone else.

09:22.750 --> 09:24.620
A few minutes alone.

09:24.620 --> 09:25.880
Can you give us that?

09:25.880 --> 09:27.420
We'll need
a yes or a no soon.

09:27.420 --> 09:28.960
And if Charlie says no,

09:28.960 --> 09:32.080
he risks being off
the transplant list for good.

09:36.830 --> 09:40.290
Charlie,
first love usually hurts.

09:40.290 --> 09:42.170
It's not supposed to
actually kill you.

09:42.170 --> 09:51.080
♪♪

09:51.080 --> 09:53.580
No! Damn it!

09:53.580 --> 09:55.460
Hey! Stop!

09:55.460 --> 09:57.080
You can't do this.

09:57.080 --> 09:58.420
I wasn't doing
anything illegal.

09:58.420 --> 10:00.080
Parking tickets.
You got to pay them.

10:00.080 --> 10:02.210
I'm going to pay them!

10:02.210 --> 10:04.170
I -- I promise.
Just...

10:04.170 --> 10:05.790
-Tell them I'll be five.
-Give me a break! I...

10:05.790 --> 10:07.580
I can give you
20 bucks.

10:07.580 --> 10:09.170
Man: Let's go.

10:09.170 --> 10:11.120
Hey, sir, come on, dude.
She's -- She's still in the car.

10:13.670 --> 10:15.790
This enough?

10:15.790 --> 10:18.460
For the inconvenience.

10:18.460 --> 10:20.210
Come on.

10:20.210 --> 10:23.210
That's a rough way
to start your day.

10:24.830 --> 10:26.120
I'll see you in Physics.

10:31.420 --> 10:32.920
Maggie:
First love is the worst.

10:32.920 --> 10:34.710
Mine had a 5:00 shadow,

10:34.710 --> 10:38.250
and he smelled like
formaldehyde -- Steve.

10:38.250 --> 10:41.880
My Gross Anatomy lab partner
with cadaver Leonard.

10:41.880 --> 10:43.620
I know you're not supposed to
name your cadavers, but --

10:43.620 --> 10:45.040
Uh, we all did.

10:45.040 --> 10:47.580
Mine was Mort,
after rigor mortis.

10:47.580 --> 10:49.000
Ah.

10:49.000 --> 10:50.460
Alex,
did you name yours?

10:50.460 --> 10:53.960
I named him "Road Kill."
It was a major bromance.

10:53.960 --> 10:56.170
Steve:
We should give him a name.

10:56.170 --> 10:57.460
Leonard?

10:57.460 --> 10:58.670
-[ Chuckles ]
-You like it?

10:58.670 --> 11:00.500
[ Giggles ]

11:00.500 --> 11:02.210
I just think we should show him
a little respect, you know?

11:02.210 --> 11:04.540
[ Giggles ]

11:04.540 --> 11:08.420
Okay, so, have you ever, uh,
you know, cut a person before?

11:08.420 --> 11:10.620
No,
it's my first time.

11:10.620 --> 11:12.620
It's my first time, too.

11:12.620 --> 11:15.120
I guess that makes us
"first-cut virgins."

11:15.120 --> 11:17.380
W-- You.

11:17.380 --> 11:19.880
You go. You start.
It's your first time.

11:19.880 --> 11:21.580
Why don't we
do it together?

11:25.580 --> 11:27.210
[ Squeaks ]

11:29.540 --> 11:33.210
Henry: Doctors,
he's ready for surgery.

11:33.210 --> 11:35.460
You talked him into it?

11:35.460 --> 11:37.250
No.
I broke up with him.

11:37.250 --> 11:39.170
What?! You what?

11:39.170 --> 11:42.290
The cosplay and poetry
and all that is fun,

11:42.290 --> 11:45.670
but I just can't be with someone
who doesn't believe in science.

11:45.670 --> 11:47.960
You were right.
It's not sweet.

11:47.960 --> 11:50.500
It's just stupid.

11:50.500 --> 11:54.380
♪ And it was only natural for me
to hope you'd come around ♪

11:54.380 --> 11:55.420
You can take a minute.

11:55.420 --> 11:57.120
Just do it.

11:57.120 --> 11:58.620
Sedate me.
Cut out my heart.

11:58.620 --> 12:00.210
It doesn't matter anymore.

12:00.210 --> 12:02.880
♪ ...Forget them ♪

12:02.880 --> 12:05.210
♪ You know things could be
so easy if you'd let them ♪

12:05.210 --> 12:06.750
Meredith: So, you're saying that
you and my mother

12:06.750 --> 12:09.880
created her laparoscopic biliary
reconstruction together?

12:09.880 --> 12:12.540
Yes.
But she won her second
Harper Avery for it.

12:12.540 --> 12:13.750
Ellis was a genius.

12:13.750 --> 12:15.750
I don't dispute that.
No one would.

12:15.750 --> 12:18.500
But that award did not
belong only to her.

12:18.500 --> 12:19.710
That award was ours.

12:19.710 --> 12:22.000
I am just supposed to
believe you, Marie?

12:22.000 --> 12:23.330
Where's the proof?

12:23.330 --> 12:24.960
Well, that's all the proof
that you need.

12:24.960 --> 12:27.120
I was gonna
publish our work together,

12:27.120 --> 12:28.880
and Ellis did it first.

12:28.880 --> 12:30.330
Without
sharing the credit.

12:30.330 --> 12:32.040
You could've just written this
last night.

12:32.040 --> 12:33.750
But I didn't.

12:33.750 --> 12:35.040
And you know I didn't.

12:35.040 --> 12:40.170
Meredith, I never married.

12:40.170 --> 12:42.790
I never cared much
for romantic relationships.

12:42.790 --> 12:45.120
I -- My closest thing to
having children was you.

12:45.120 --> 12:48.750
My friendship with your mother
was the greatest love of my life

12:48.750 --> 12:51.250
and when she betrayed me,
it was unimaginably painful.

12:51.250 --> 12:54.040
I went home,
I ran my father's company,

12:54.040 --> 12:55.830
I never returned
to the United States

12:55.830 --> 12:58.120
or to my surgical practice.

12:58.120 --> 13:00.120
She broke me.

13:00.120 --> 13:02.750
♪ And I don't wanna lose you
now, or ever ♪

13:02.750 --> 13:04.960
Do you ever think maybe
you gave her too much power?

13:04.960 --> 13:07.040
[ Sighs ]

13:07.040 --> 13:09.620
♪♪

13:09.620 --> 13:11.750
I'm sure that's true.

13:11.750 --> 13:13.920
But now
I believe I have a right

13:13.920 --> 13:16.040
to the work that your mother
stole from me.

13:16.040 --> 13:19.460
I believe I was meant to be more
in this life

13:19.460 --> 13:21.830
and the person that I trusted
the most in this world

13:21.830 --> 13:23.880
took that from me.

13:23.880 --> 13:26.620
So if you want my patent,

13:26.620 --> 13:30.080
you must make a public statement
that the Ellis Grey Procedure

13:30.080 --> 13:32.920
is now
the Grey-Cerone Procedure.

13:32.920 --> 13:34.080
♪ ...Ever ♪

13:34.080 --> 13:35.880
It's up to you.

13:35.880 --> 13:39.670
♪ No, I don't wanna
lose you now ♪

13:39.670 --> 13:42.040
[ Door opens, closes ]

13:47.960 --> 13:49.750
Meredith: Is it true?

13:49.750 --> 13:51.500
Was my mother's second Harper
Avery inspired by a stolen idea?

13:51.500 --> 13:52.830
What?

13:52.830 --> 13:54.080
Look, all I heard were --

13:54.080 --> 13:55.290
Rumors,
yes, you've said.

13:55.290 --> 13:57.880
But you didn't think
this was worth mentioning?

13:57.880 --> 14:00.830
Inspiration
is intangible.

14:00.830 --> 14:02.210
It comes in flashes.

14:02.210 --> 14:04.380
I mean,
people give you pieces.

14:04.380 --> 14:06.750
Something Maggie said
about a -- a magic wand

14:06.750 --> 14:08.330
inspired my cancer pen.

14:08.330 --> 14:10.210
But if I win that contest,

14:10.210 --> 14:12.250
it will not be
the Webber/Pierce pen.

14:12.250 --> 14:13.750
It'll be mine.

14:15.580 --> 14:18.790
Meredith, I didn't tell you
about the rumors

14:18.790 --> 14:21.500
because I don't
believe they're true.

14:21.500 --> 14:25.460
And it's not up to you
to undo your mother's legacy

14:25.460 --> 14:28.460
when she's not here to defend
her side of the story.

14:28.460 --> 14:33.920
♪♪

14:33.920 --> 14:35.170
We're gonna put you under now.
Are you ready?

14:37.790 --> 14:39.210
[ Whispering ] Charlie,

14:39.210 --> 14:41.670
you have to vow that
you're going to survive.

14:41.670 --> 14:44.120
Because you have to
fight for Henry.

14:44.120 --> 14:45.670
True love
survives arguments.

14:45.670 --> 14:47.670
Sometimes it even survives
break-ups,

14:47.670 --> 14:50.290
so you have to live, and then
you have to fight for him.

14:50.290 --> 14:52.210
Okay?

14:52.210 --> 14:59.330
♪♪

14:59.330 --> 15:00.580
April:
Why are you still here?

15:00.580 --> 15:02.420
Looking for food,
but this is just vodka,

15:02.420 --> 15:04.920
baby food,
and questionable cheese.

15:04.920 --> 15:06.420
Do you like paella?

15:06.420 --> 15:07.500
There's a great place
a few blocks away

15:07.500 --> 15:09.420
that, uh, we can --

15:09.420 --> 15:11.620
Are you stalling to see if
we'll have sex again?

15:11.620 --> 15:14.000
No, but I -- I like
the way you're thinking.

15:14.000 --> 15:15.540
Except
paella isn't sex food.

15:15.540 --> 15:17.540
Too rich.

15:17.540 --> 15:19.830
I'll just have this road-yogurt,
then I'll go.

15:19.830 --> 15:21.670
Oh.
-Sorry.

15:21.670 --> 15:24.920
You have a daughter.

15:24.920 --> 15:27.000
I'm gonna say --

15:27.000 --> 15:32.750
Judging by the toys ruining
your decor, I'm gonna say 2-ish.

15:32.750 --> 15:34.210
Please don't do that.

15:34.210 --> 15:35.540
Do what?

15:35.540 --> 15:38.000
Feign an interest in me
to get me back into bed.

15:38.000 --> 15:40.210
I will probably go back to bed
with you regardless

15:40.210 --> 15:41.790
'cause you're pretty good
at sex.

15:41.790 --> 15:44.250
Hmm.
So, conversation
is not necessary.

15:44.250 --> 15:45.540
Well, thank you
for the "pretty good."

15:45.540 --> 15:47.120
It's an understatement,
but I'll take it.

15:47.120 --> 15:50.540
And I'm not feigning anything.
This is...fascinating.

15:50.540 --> 15:52.620
Yeah? What is?

15:52.620 --> 15:54.460
Well, when I met you,
months ago,

15:54.460 --> 15:56.670
Amelia Shepherd had given you
her Power of Attorney.

15:56.670 --> 15:59.710
She trusted you
with her life.

15:59.710 --> 16:00.920
You remember that?

16:00.920 --> 16:02.170
We barely spoke.

16:02.170 --> 16:03.830
Oh,
I'm incredibly observant.

16:03.830 --> 16:04.960
And -- And --
-Oh.

16:04.960 --> 16:07.670
Look -- L-look at your home,
here.

16:07.670 --> 16:11.620
Fun toddler detritus,
lots of light, warmth, books.

16:11.620 --> 16:12.960
Your point?

16:12.960 --> 16:14.960
The woman
I met last night?

16:14.960 --> 16:17.620
[ Chuckling ]
She doesn't live here.
Mm?

16:17.620 --> 16:19.830
And she's not a person you trust
with a Power of Attorney.

16:19.830 --> 16:22.330
I'm not sure I should trust you
with my...penis again.

16:22.330 --> 16:24.380
That woman
scares me a little.

16:24.380 --> 16:25.670
In a "pretty good" way,
but, uh --

16:25.670 --> 16:27.000
But what?

16:27.000 --> 16:30.290
How did that woman
become this woman?

16:30.290 --> 16:31.670
I'm not gonna get into this
with you.

16:31.670 --> 16:33.120
Uh, no -- No, no, no. No, no.
No, no, no.

16:33.120 --> 16:34.960
L-- No.
Let me do it.

16:34.960 --> 16:35.790
-Okay.
-Oh, yeah.

16:35.790 --> 16:36.790
All right.

16:36.790 --> 16:38.170
Uh, alcoholism.

16:38.170 --> 16:39.750
Drugs.

16:39.750 --> 16:41.420
Cancer diagnosis.

16:41.420 --> 16:43.670
No?
Uh...physical trauma?

16:43.670 --> 16:45.620
Uh...dead relative.

16:45.620 --> 16:47.500
Dead pet.

16:47.500 --> 16:49.500
Uh, dead beloved
TV-show character.

16:49.500 --> 16:50.750
-Oh, my God.
-None of these?

16:50.750 --> 16:52.880
Okay, that leaves,
um, metal illness,

16:52.880 --> 16:55.620
acute clinical depression,
crisis of faith.

16:55.620 --> 16:57.880
-[ Chuckling ] Stop.
-Crisis of faith.

16:57.880 --> 16:59.500
-No.
-Mm-hmm.

16:59.500 --> 17:00.960
God is dead.
-No.

17:00.960 --> 17:02.000
Ah, yes.

17:02.000 --> 17:05.000
No, He's not dead.

17:05.000 --> 17:08.120
I just hate Him so much
I wish He was.

17:09.330 --> 17:11.830
Ah.

17:14.670 --> 17:17.000
I don't think my heart
ever looked this healthy.

17:17.000 --> 17:18.580
Even when I was born,

17:18.580 --> 17:21.830
I think it was like a raisin
with thunderstorms inside.

17:21.830 --> 17:23.580
Maggie:
Heart is detached.

17:23.580 --> 17:25.580
Wow, it's even worse
than the studies.

17:25.580 --> 17:28.120
There's nothing but adhesions
and an aneurysm.

17:28.120 --> 17:29.460
Naming that heart
before you trash it?

17:29.460 --> 17:30.500
Since you're into
naming medical waste?

17:30.500 --> 17:32.210
Ha-ha-ha.

17:32.210 --> 17:34.830
Teacher Assistant:
Okay, people, wrap it up.

17:34.830 --> 17:36.330
Good.

17:36.330 --> 17:37.620
Clean up and sign out
when you're done.

17:37.620 --> 17:39.120
Anatomy test tomorrow.

17:39.120 --> 17:41.670
What happens to Len--
the cadaver?

17:41.670 --> 17:42.960
Like,
where does he go now?

17:42.960 --> 17:46.380
Crematorium.
Finish by 5:00.

17:46.380 --> 17:48.170
I guess this is it.
[ Chuckles ]

17:48.170 --> 17:50.250
We're done.

17:50.250 --> 17:51.920
Feels weird.

17:51.920 --> 17:53.040
We should hang out!

17:55.080 --> 17:56.540
To have a funeral
for Leonard.

17:56.540 --> 17:58.460
H-He deserves that.

17:58.460 --> 17:59.790
You're right.

17:59.790 --> 18:02.500
Yes. But we can't
steal a cadaver body.

18:02.500 --> 18:03.500
Can we?

18:03.500 --> 18:04.960
Highly unlikely.

18:08.790 --> 18:10.210
I'll cover you.

18:10.210 --> 18:19.040
♪♪

18:19.040 --> 18:23.210
Okay, wait, you stole
a dissected cadaver heart?

18:23.210 --> 18:26.040
We needed something to bury,
and it was very symbolic.

18:26.040 --> 18:28.880
You stole a human heart so you
could see a boy one more time.

18:28.880 --> 18:29.880
At a made-up funeral.

18:29.880 --> 18:31.420
You were so weird.

18:31.420 --> 18:32.580
I was young.

18:32.580 --> 18:34.250
You were weird
and creepy.

18:34.250 --> 18:36.040
You're so nice now.
What happened?

18:39.670 --> 18:41.000
What's wrong?

18:41.000 --> 18:42.620
The heart doesn't fit.

18:42.620 --> 18:44.250
What do you mean
it doesn't fit?

18:44.250 --> 18:47.620
The new heart is too big
for Charlie's chest.

18:58.080 --> 18:59.420
Why the hell didn't we get
precise measurements?

18:59.420 --> 19:00.670
The measurements
were precise.

19:00.670 --> 19:02.000
This is probably swelling
from resuscitative edema.

19:02.000 --> 19:03.540
Should we put him
back on ECMO?

19:03.540 --> 19:05.000
No, he's already been on ECMO
for far longer than he should.

19:05.000 --> 19:07.330
Okay, what if we give him
a total artificial heart?

19:07.330 --> 19:08.750
No.
We're gonna make this one work.

19:08.750 --> 19:10.790
-How? There's no space.
-Well, we'll create a space.

19:10.790 --> 19:12.120
We'll do a sternal
reconstruction.

19:12.120 --> 19:13.250
I mean, we'll make the chest
fit the heart.

19:13.250 --> 19:14.880
We can do that, right?

19:17.710 --> 19:19.330
We'll attach the heart now,

19:19.330 --> 19:21.620
and we'll leave him open
in the CCU overnight,

19:21.620 --> 19:22.790
and pump him full of Lasix,

19:22.790 --> 19:24.330
and then when
the swelling goes down,

19:24.330 --> 19:26.880
we can go back in and cover it
with a sternal muscle flap.

19:26.880 --> 19:28.460
We might need to
take out the sternum

19:28.460 --> 19:30.170
and we'll need Avery to close,
but we can do this.

19:32.790 --> 19:35.750
I'll update his mom.

19:35.750 --> 19:38.710
What do you mean
you'll leave him open overnight?

19:38.710 --> 19:41.960
Well, we won't close his chest
until the swelling goes down.

19:41.960 --> 19:44.290
So his heart
will just be unprotected?

19:44.290 --> 19:45.790
We'll -- We'll cover him
in Ioban wrap.

19:45.790 --> 19:47.250
What is that?

19:47.250 --> 19:48.880
It's, uh -- It's kind of like,
uh, plastic wrap

19:48.880 --> 19:50.710
but, uh, medical-grade.

19:50.710 --> 19:52.540
You want to cover my son's heart
in plastic wrap?

19:52.540 --> 19:54.170
Just until
the swelling goes down.

19:54.170 --> 19:55.540
He'll be in the ICU.
He'll be monitored.

19:55.540 --> 19:59.210
[ Scoffs ]

19:59.210 --> 20:01.920
[ Voice breaking ]
We're in this world alone.

20:01.920 --> 20:05.500
It's him and me.

20:05.500 --> 20:08.080
It's always just been
him and me,

20:08.080 --> 20:10.000
and I will break if he doesn't
come out of this.

20:10.000 --> 20:12.710
You understand?

20:12.710 --> 20:15.330
If we broke
that boy's heart

20:15.330 --> 20:18.540
and sent him into a surgery
he doesn't recover from...

20:20.750 --> 20:21.790
...I will break.

20:23.540 --> 20:25.120
They're coming!
They're coming!

20:25.120 --> 20:26.120
Hide!

20:26.120 --> 20:27.880
Mom.

20:27.880 --> 20:29.500
Mom!
Come here. Mom.

20:29.500 --> 20:30.500
-I can hear them.
-No, no, no! Mom!

20:30.500 --> 20:31.380
I can hear them.
There's so many.

20:31.380 --> 20:33.210
Let me see it -- see it!
Let me see it!
We're not safe here!

20:33.210 --> 20:35.750
Mom! Come here.
Come here. Come here.

20:35.750 --> 20:36.920
There you go.
There you go.

20:36.920 --> 20:38.960
Hey, it's me. It's me.
It's Alex.

20:38.960 --> 20:40.210
-Alex. Alex.
-All right. All right.

20:40.210 --> 20:41.380
They're all gone.
They're all gone.

20:41.380 --> 20:42.580
There was one.
I had to kill one of them.

20:42.580 --> 20:44.210
Can you give me the -- the pills
and the glass right there?

20:44.210 --> 20:45.290
It's on the counter.
-Is it over?

20:45.290 --> 20:46.380
She just forgot to
take her pills this morning.

20:46.380 --> 20:48.040
[ Panting ] It's okay.
No, I -- it's okay.

20:48.040 --> 20:49.460
I know. I know.

20:51.750 --> 20:53.620
Mom's been updated.

20:53.620 --> 20:55.170
Good.
4-O prolene.

20:55.170 --> 20:56.920
Can you follow me?

20:56.920 --> 21:04.420
♪ He makes me smaller with every
embrace that I ask for ♪

21:04.420 --> 21:07.790
♪♪

21:07.790 --> 21:14.790
♪ Sit between the sheets of
paper he writes on and I ♪

21:14.790 --> 21:18.670
♪♪

21:18.670 --> 21:23.670
♪ I keep on shrinking
and he stays the same ♪

21:23.670 --> 21:29.080
♪♪

21:29.080 --> 21:30.960
Alex: It's been re-warming
for almost 15 minutes,

21:30.960 --> 21:32.830
and we're at 53 degrees.

21:32.830 --> 21:34.170
It should be
beating by now.

21:34.170 --> 21:35.880
-Wait.
-It's warm and perfused.

21:35.880 --> 21:37.670
Something's not right.

21:37.670 --> 21:39.330
We still haven't fully rested
and re-warmed the heart yet.

21:39.330 --> 21:40.580
Wait one more degree.

21:40.580 --> 21:42.250
And risk
losing his heart?

21:42.250 --> 21:44.880
Look, this kid can't handle
another complication today.

21:44.880 --> 21:51.580
♪♪

21:51.580 --> 21:53.460
Damn it!
It's not working!

21:53.460 --> 21:54.750
[ Monitor beeping ]
-Wait, wait! It's fibrillating!

21:54.750 --> 21:56.170
Internal paddles now.

21:56.170 --> 21:58.000
Charge to 20.

21:58.000 --> 21:59.620
[ Paddles whine ]
Clear.

21:59.620 --> 22:01.500
[ Thump ]

22:03.170 --> 22:04.290
Jo: Nothing.

22:04.290 --> 22:05.500
Charge to 30.
[ Paddles whine ]

22:05.500 --> 22:06.830
Clear.
[ Thump ]

22:06.830 --> 22:08.670
Come on, Charlie.
You said you'd fight, so fight.

22:08.670 --> 22:10.460
Fight for him.
-Charge to 50.

22:10.460 --> 22:11.880
Alex, wait, wait!

22:11.880 --> 22:13.670
[ Monitor beeping ]

22:13.670 --> 22:16.460
[ All sigh ]

22:16.460 --> 22:21.750
♪ Used up all of my words,
I can't read him anymore ♪

22:21.750 --> 22:23.420
Chris:
Why do you study so much?

22:23.420 --> 22:25.170
Brooke: I have to get out
of my car somehow.

22:25.170 --> 22:27.670
Why? I like it.

22:27.670 --> 22:30.120
It's private, no parents,
kind of roomy,

22:30.120 --> 22:32.790
smells like French fries
on most days.

22:32.790 --> 22:34.420
Yeah.

22:34.420 --> 22:36.750
Come back in the winter
and see how you like it then.

22:36.750 --> 22:38.880
Hmm.

22:38.880 --> 22:40.620
Move in to my house.

22:40.620 --> 22:41.920
Stay with us.

22:41.920 --> 22:43.420
Right.

22:43.420 --> 22:45.040
Your perfect parents
are gonna be okay with you

22:45.040 --> 22:46.330
telling them
you're hot for homeless.

22:46.330 --> 22:47.540
[ Chuckling ] Stop it.

22:47.540 --> 22:48.540
Hey,
Mom and Dad Cleaver,

22:48.540 --> 22:50.540
this is
my street-rat girlfriend.

22:50.540 --> 22:52.880
She brought breakfast from
the dumpster behind the IHOP.

22:52.880 --> 22:55.040
That is not
who you are.

22:55.040 --> 22:57.380
And it's not
who they are.

22:57.380 --> 22:59.540
Come on, they'll love you
as much as I do.

23:02.710 --> 23:05.330
I might love them for teaching
you to say stuff like that.

23:05.330 --> 23:07.000
[ Chuckles ]

23:07.000 --> 23:08.380
It was pretty good,
right?

23:11.540 --> 23:14.330
[ Monitor beeping,
respirator hissing ]

23:32.790 --> 23:35.670
You're still here.

23:35.670 --> 23:37.290
[ Voice breaking ]
What happened?

23:37.290 --> 23:38.380
Uh...

23:38.380 --> 23:40.790
Why is he still --
What happened?

23:40.790 --> 23:43.080
There was a complication
during surgery.

23:43.080 --> 23:47.040
We have to keep him open
overnight.

23:48.750 --> 23:50.210
[ Crying ]
I didn't mean it.

23:52.380 --> 23:55.290
I only broke up with him so he
would take the heart and live.

23:55.290 --> 23:57.830
I thought -- I thought
I would come back

23:57.830 --> 24:00.580
and he would be awake
and sitting up

24:00.580 --> 24:03.380
and I would kiss him
and he would thank me.

24:03.380 --> 24:04.750
I...

24:04.750 --> 24:06.330
I broke up with him.

24:09.000 --> 24:11.380
I called him stupid.

24:11.380 --> 24:13.830
That was the last thing
I said to him.

24:13.830 --> 24:17.380
[ Breathing shakily ]

24:17.380 --> 24:19.710
It's okay.

24:19.710 --> 24:22.040
It's all right.

24:30.290 --> 24:31.620
Woman on PA:
Dr. Hoffner to Oncology.
Dr. Hoffner to Oncology.

24:31.620 --> 24:33.420
Hey. Charlie's labs
and vitals are improving.

24:33.420 --> 24:34.880
Pierce said she's gonna
stick around tonight,

24:34.880 --> 24:36.380
so we can go home.

24:36.380 --> 24:37.620
I'm good here.

24:37.620 --> 24:39.500
You need sleep.

24:39.500 --> 24:42.710
How about I order us dinner
and then we talk?

24:42.710 --> 24:44.920
There's nothing
to talk about.

24:44.920 --> 24:47.830
I'm not -- I'm not
letting you out of here

24:47.830 --> 24:49.460
until you talk to me.

24:49.460 --> 24:51.250
[ Chuckling ]
Oh, mature.

24:51.250 --> 24:53.080
Oh, I-I'm the one
who's not being mature?

24:53.080 --> 24:54.540
You've been brooding
all day.

24:54.540 --> 24:55.540
I'm not brooding.

24:55.540 --> 24:56.790
There's a patient
that's critical.

24:56.790 --> 24:57.750
I told you,
Maggie's staying tonight.

24:57.750 --> 24:59.380
Great.
So will I.

24:59.380 --> 25:01.290
Then you can go home
and work on your applications.

25:01.290 --> 25:02.540
Oh, y-you're punishing me

25:02.540 --> 25:05.000
for taking steps
to further my career?

25:05.000 --> 25:06.290
Of course not!
I just --

25:06.290 --> 25:08.000
I-I didn't think you'd be
so excited to --

25:08.000 --> 25:09.880
to consider leaving Seattle.

25:09.880 --> 25:11.040
Because I can!

25:11.040 --> 25:12.170
Because for the first time,

25:12.170 --> 25:14.330
I can do exactly
what I want to do.

25:14.330 --> 25:15.580
I have freedom now,

25:15.580 --> 25:17.290
I have opportunities
that I didn't have before

25:17.290 --> 25:19.880
because I was afraid that
Paul was gonna come find me.

25:19.880 --> 25:21.880
You know what,
I can apply anywhere now.

25:21.880 --> 25:23.290
I don't have to
hide in Seattle.

25:23.290 --> 25:25.420
I thought that you,
of all people, would get that.

25:25.420 --> 25:29.040
Look, I'm happy Paul's gone,
and I'm happy you're free.

25:29.040 --> 25:31.500
I just didn't realize he was
the only one keeping you here.

25:43.750 --> 25:46.460
-You paged.
-Hi.

25:46.460 --> 25:49.120
Yeah, I'm sorry it's so late,
I just need a quick consult.

25:49.120 --> 25:50.790
Uh, sure.
Yeah, no problem.

25:50.790 --> 25:52.250
It's a failed
sternal closure

25:52.250 --> 25:54.750
after a heart transplant
due to edema.

25:54.750 --> 25:56.960
I'm gonna go in tomorrow and
reconstruct the chest cavity,

25:56.960 --> 25:58.330
but I was thinking
that we could

25:58.330 --> 26:00.380
cover the chest defect
with a flap.

26:00.380 --> 26:02.540
Yeah, if it's a huge defect,
I would do an omental flap.

26:02.540 --> 26:04.330
Otherwise, you do
a sternal muscular flap,

26:04.330 --> 26:05.790
provide some cushion
for the heart.

26:05.790 --> 26:07.080
Great. Thank you.

26:07.080 --> 26:08.170
Sure.

26:08.170 --> 26:10.170
I mean, I was kind of hoping
you'd page me

26:10.170 --> 26:11.920
